docs.abstract: Jerome Powell said that strong economic growth gives Federal Reserve officials room to be patient, and he emphasized the institution’s political independence.
docs.snippet: Jerome Powell said that strong economic growth gives Federal Reserve officials room to be patient, and he emphasized the institution’s political independence.
docs.lead_paragraph: Jerome H. Powell, the chair of the Federal Reserve, said on Friday that resilient economic growth is giving the central bank the flexibility to be patient before cutting interest rates.

headline.main: Fed Chair Says Central Bank Need Not ‘Hurry’ to Cut Rates
headline.print_headline: Fed Chair Says Central Bank Need Not Rush to Cut Rates

docs.abstract: The Fed’s preferred inflation gauge climbed 2.5 percent in the year through February, in line with economists’ expectations.
docs.snippet: The Fed’s preferred inflation gauge climbed 2.5 percent in the year through February, in line with economists’ expectations.
docs.lead_paragraph: The latest reading of the Federal Reserve’s favorite inflation gauge was in line with economists’ expectations, as price increases hovered above the central bank’s target even after months of cooling.

headline.main: A Key Inflation Gauge Hovers Above Fed’s Target
headline.print_headline: Key Gauge Of Inflation Still Topping Fed’s Target

docs.abstract: After enjoying decades of prosperity, the country has hit stubborn economic turbulence.
docs.snippet: After enjoying decades of prosperity, the country has hit stubborn economic turbulence.
docs.lead_paragraph: For nearly three decades, Australia seemed to have a sort of get-out-of-jail card that allowed it to glide through the dot-com bust and the global financial crisis without a recession, while its citizens mostly enjoyed high wages, affordable housing and golden prospects.

headline.main: Happy-Go-Lucky Australia Is Feeling Neither Happy, Nor Lucky
headline.print_headline: In Wealthy, Stable Australia, the Economic Gloom Is Proving Hard to Shake

docs.abstract: A wave of strikes by German workers, feeling the sting of inflation and stagnant growth, is the latest sign of the bleak outlook for Europe’s economic powerhouse.
docs.snippet: A wave of strikes by German workers, feeling the sting of inflation and stagnant growth, is the latest sign of the bleak outlook for Europe’s economic powerhouse.
docs.lead_paragraph: For those striking at the gates of the SRW scrap metal plant, just outside Germany’s eastern city of Leipzig, time can be counted not just in days — 136 so far — but in the thousands of card games played, the liters of coffee imbibed and the armfuls of firewood burned.

headline.main: ‘Strike Madness’ Hits Germany While Its Economy Stumbles
headline.print_headline: Wave of Strikes Hits Germany While Its Economy Stumbles

byline.original: By Christopher F. Schuetze and Erika Solomon

docs.abstract: Japan’s improved labor force participation for women is a reminder not to assume that job market limits are clear and finite.
docs.snippet: Japan’s improved labor force participation for women is a reminder not to assume that job market limits are clear and finite.
docs.lead_paragraph: Japan’s economy has rocketed into the headlines this year as inflation returns for the first time in decades, workers win wage gains and the Bank of Japan raises interest rates for the first time in 17 years.

headline.main: Japan’s Labor Market Has a Lesson for the Fed: Women Can Surprise You

docs.abstract: Inflation had been moderating steadily, but it is now hovering around 3 percent. Will lowering it fully to normal levels prove difficult?
docs.snippet: Inflation had been moderating steadily, but it is now hovering around 3 percent. Will lowering it fully to normal levels prove difficult?
docs.lead_paragraph: Slowing America’s rapid inflation has been an unexpectedly painless process so far. High interest rates are making it expensive to take out a mortgage or borrow to start a business, but they have not slammed the brakes on economic growth or drastically pushed up unemployment.

headline.main: Fed Meets Amid Worries That Inflation Progress Might Stall
headline.print_headline: Fed Meets Amid Worries That Progress on Inflation Might Stall

docs.abstract: Traders are closely watching once-obscure economic data, prompting more scrutiny of how widely the government distributes the information.
docs.snippet: Traders are closely watching once-obscure economic data, prompting more scrutiny of how widely the government distributes the information.
docs.lead_paragraph: One afternoon in late February, an employee at the Bureau of Labor Statistics sent an email about an obscure detail in the way the government calculates inflation — and set off an unlikely firestorm.

headline.main: Email ‘Mistake’ on Inflation Data Prompts Questions on What Is Shared
headline.print_headline: Email on Inflation Data That Puzzled Economists Causes More Confusion

byline.original: By Ben Casselman and Jeanna Smialek

docs.abstract: President Biden and former President Donald J. Trump offer vastly different policy paths on almost every aspect of the economy.
docs.snippet: President Biden and former President Donald J. Trump offer vastly different policy paths on almost every aspect of the economy.
docs.lead_paragraph: President Biden in his budget this week staked out major economic battle lines with former President Donald J. Trump, the presumptive Republican presidential nominee. The proposal offers the nation a glimpse of the diverging directions that retirement programs, taxes, trade and energy policy could take depending on the outcome of the November election.

headline.main: Biden Budget Lays Out Economic Battle Lines Against Trump
headline.print_headline: Biden Sets Economic Battle Lines With Trump

docs.abstract: The president’s $7.3 trillion budget proposal for the next fiscal year includes about $3 trillion in deficit reduction over a decade, largely from raising taxes on high earners and corporations.
docs.snippet: The president’s $7.3 trillion budget proposal for the next fiscal year includes about $3 trillion in deficit reduction over a decade, largely from raising taxes on high earners and corporations.
docs.lead_paragraph: President Biden proposed a $7.3 trillion budget on Monday packed with tax increases on corporations and high earners, new spending on social programs and a wide range of efforts to combat high consumer costs like housing and college tuition.

headline.main: Biden’s Budget Underscores Divide With Republicans and Trump
headline.print_headline: Biden’s Budget Meant to Draw Line vs. Trump

docs.abstract: Voters feel slightly better about the economy as inflation recedes, but partisan divides remain deep, a Times/Siena poll found.
docs.snippet: Voters feel slightly better about the economy as inflation recedes, but partisan divides remain deep, a Times/Siena poll found.
docs.lead_paragraph: Eight months before the election, Americans feel slightly better about the state of the economy as inflation recedes and the labor market remains stable, but President Biden doesn’t appear to be benefiting.

headline.main: Brighter Economic Mood Isn’t Translating Into Support for Biden
headline.print_headline: Better Mood On Economy, Not for Biden

byline.original: By Ben Casselman, Lydia DePillis and Christine Zhang
